    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1933-06-20T15:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1933-06-20T15:00:00-05:00" n="474"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d474">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">550.S1 Monetary Commission/5: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chairman of the American Delegation</hi> (<persName
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Hull</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Acting Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="62" xml:id="d474fn62">Transmitted to President Roosevelt, aboard U. S.
                        S. <hi rend="italic">Ellis</hi>, as telegram No. 5, June 20, 6 p.m.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1933-06-20T21:00:00+01:00"
                            >June 20, 1933—9 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received June 20—4:34 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>47. For the President from Warburg. Discussion in second committee of Monetary
                    Commission was centered entirely on our resolution<note n="63" xml:id="d474fn63"
                        >See fourth resolution in “Memorandum on Policy for American Delegation,”
                            <ref target="#pg_622">pp. 622</ref>, <ref target="#pg_626">626</ref>;
                        for discussion, see <hi rend="italic">Journal of the Monetary and Economic
                            Conference</hi>, pp. 66–67.</note> introduced yesterday. At today’s
                    session committee unanimously accepted sections (<hi rend="italic">a</hi>) and
                        (<hi rend="italic">b</hi>) and referred remainder of first half to
                    subcommittee appointed for working out technical details of an eventual
                    permanent gold standard and referred second half of resolution relating to
                    silver to second subcommittee under chairmanship of Pittman. This result highly
                    gratifying and precisely what <pb facs="0753" n="651" xml:id="pg_651"/> we were
                    working for. First committee has so far debated resolution introduced by
                        Chamberlain<note n="64" xml:id="d474fn64">Neville Chamberlain, British
                        Chancelor of the Exchequer.</note> on immediate monetary and credit policy
                    which closely resembles first half of our corresponding resolution. We have not
                    joined debate since through Cox chairmanship we can get in our work more easily
                    in drafting committee which will probably be appointed tomorrow. [Warburg.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
